            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "No. You're misunderstanding it.\r\n\r\n```\r\ncdef int foo() nogil except -1:\r\n    return something_can_be_minus_1\r\n```\r\n\r\nYou should **never** return `-1` from this function. `-1` is used *by Cython* to indicate that an exception has occurred. If `-1` is also a valid return value then use `except? -1`.\r\n\r\n```\r\ncpdef void bar() except *:\r\n    foo()\r\n    print('here')\r\n```\r\n\r\nCython will internally check the return value of `foo` and propagate the exception if it's `-1`. Thus the code will work as intended.\r\n\r\nFeel free to suggest improvements to the documentation if you don't feel it explains it well enough.\r\n\r\n",
